**[Scene tag — Vareth Opens the Debate]**
- Vareth has prepared his speech and delivers it with evident forethought.
- He establishes that this is not a fashion — libraries, taverns, chapter houses, and courts are all arguing.
- He mentions the three duels at Candlekeep and Sister Yvenne's threat.

**GM** — *Vareth begins his prepared speech*
> "He says, drag him!"
> "You… you are an excellent person for us to have this conversation with, because we are now confronted with the problem of our age."

**Grygum** — *playing along*
> "Yes, the, the question of our age, of course."

**GM** — *Vareth's speech, verbatim*
> "Brother Grygum, I will take you to the several schools, the material I have collected over the last several years on the debate of the question of our age."

**Grygum** — *affirming*
> "Aye."

**GM** — *continuing*
> "But before you read the polemics, I must tell you what they are all about."
> "You can sense that he's prepared this speech for some time."

**Grygum** — *welcoming a summary*
> "Good, I love hearing summaries."

**GM** — *Vareth's core statement*
> "They are not about a chess game. They are not about a dwarf, however remarkable. They are not even primarily about the late war. They are about the question of the age. I do not say this lightly. I have been keeping this corner of the library for 41 years, and I know what a fashion looks like."
> "This is not a fashion. The libraries are arguing. The taverns are arguing. The chapter houses are arguing. The courts of two cities have asked for written opinions."

**Grygum** — *with mock drama*
> "Yes, what drama in our time?"

**GM** — *the Stroud Eye pamphlets and the duels*
> "Yes, the Stroud Lake, Stroud Eye pamphlets have crossed the Sea of Swords."
> "We have had three duels at Candlekeep over which polemic shelf gets the larger window. Three in a library where nobody has dueled in 200 years. Sister Yvetne threatens to confiscate everyone's book plates. She has not yet, but I expect it."

---

**[Scene tag — The Three Schools of Thought]**
- Vareth lays out the Stroudite, Bahamutian, and Draconic schools in sequence.
- Grygum reacts to each in turn.

**GM** — *the core question*
> "What is being asked beneath the chest and the dragons and the partisan colors is this. What kind of universe do we live in?"

**GM** — *the Stroudite school*
> "The Stroud School answers, a universe in which mortal choice is sovereign. The gods exist, the dragons exists, Providence may or may not exist, but the choosing belongs to the chooser, and is not borrowed, and is not alone from any one throne above or below."

**Grygum** — *responding to the Stroudite position*
> "Yes, the choice belongs to the chooser. This is a, this is the principle that I can get behind."

**GM** — *elaborating on Stroudite implications*
> "By this reading, Tiamat was denied her power because a dwarf chose, and the chain of choices that followed was a chain of free acts. Strike out anyone, and the chain falls."
> "But you're a cleric of Bahamut. Perhaps you wish to hear the Bahamutian theory."

**Grygum** — *on his sympathies*
> "I am inclined toward the, toward the Stroudite, but,"
> "I, I will listen, I will listen politely."

**GM** — *the Bahamutian school*
> "The Bahamutian School answers, a universe in which divine providence prevails. Bahamut moved his pieces beforehand. The dragons obeyed because they were agents of a just god. The mortals, Stroud included, served as instruments of providence. By this reading, choice was real, but not sovereign. Stroud chose what he was fitted to choose."
> "The chain was an arranged chain."
> "Providence prevails."

**Grygum** — *sensing a fallacy*
> "I cannot put my finger on it, but I feel, I feel there must be a fallacy."

**GM** — *introducing the Draconic school*
> "Well, there's a third school of thought that perhaps your friend,"
> "Zalthir."
> "Can remember some. Because the Dragon School answers, most quietly, a universe in which ancient agency rules, and mortals operate in the frames the Dragon Set. Protenthor chose to honor Stroud's move because Protanther is honorable, not because Bahamut compelled him."
> "The metallic dragons followed Protanther because they trust their elders, not because the gods commanded them. The choosing is real, but the scope of the choosing is what the dragons permit."

**GM** — *Vareth's summation of the stakes*
> "Three answers, three universes. They cannot be all right at the same time, and the question, Brother Grygum, matters in a way I've never seen a question rather. Because if the Stroud School is right, the gods are constrained, and the central truth of the cosmos is the irreducible mortal choice."
> "That no power above or below can possess. The good gods cannot manufacture our mercy. The evil gods cannot manufacture our cruelty. There is no procedure that produces the human outcome reliably, because the human is not a stone or a star or a level, or a lever, and refuses when every calculation says they should obey."

---

**[Scene tag — Grygum Proposes a Fourth School]**
- Grygum interrupts to propose fixed points as a philosophical compromise.
- Vareth has a moment of "utter panic" at the prospect of a fourth school.

**Grygum** — *proposing the fourth school*
> "But… but what if there's a fourth?"
> "What if there are certain fixed points around which our actions must revolve? And the closer we come to one of those fixed points, the more constrained we are, but between them, perhaps we have a great deal of freedom of action."

**GM** — *Vareth's reaction*
> "He has that moment of utter panic."
> "He goes, a fourth school of thought?"

**Grygum** — *playfully*
> "Hi! Have you considered the other possibilities?"

**GM** — *Vareth's excitement*
> "No, no, and this is why I am so ecstatic to see you! Who cares about the Bahamutians, who think that it's all arranged by first principles, or the dragons, who think that they know how the world looks? He goes, I don't care."

**Grygum** — *amused*
> "That would be much better!"

**GM** — *Vareth's enthusiasm overflows*
> "You have excited me in ways that I could not imagine."

**Grygum** — *wryly*
> "I feel attracted."

**GM** — *Vareth insisting Grygum stay*
> "More than one track. Brother Grygum, I will insist that you not leave Candlekeep for several weeks. Having said that, we will have to conduct the research to ensure that we have done a complete survey of all the material before we can…"
> "Yes, I'm… oh, I'm… this is so exciting!"

**Grygum** — *satisfied*
> "Yes, very satisfying."

**GM** — *Vareth naming the discovery*
> "A fourth principle! Perhaps a compromise! This was not a triangle that everyone argued, but a square!"

**Grygum** — *beginning to respond*
> "Yes, so…"

**GM** — *the quadrangle / center of the circle*
> "Quadrangles."
> "A quadrangle, or perhaps it was the center of the circle! That the three triangles, the three points, described a circle, and this was its center."

**GM** — *Vareth's deeper theorizing about a god shaping evidence*
> "He pauses and goes, I am afraid I do not know what the answer is."
> "But apparently, the world has been arranging it around it while we argue. I tell you, Stroud, we have a god who wished to control the outcome of mortal lives, would not need to compel a single hand. She would only shape the rules of the evidence. The form of polemic, the architecture of a chapter house, the quiet."

**Grygum** — *connecting it to his theory*
> "This falls in very, very conveniently with my theory."

**GM** — *Vareth relaying the Stroudite counter*
> "Or that… and that Stroud, on the other hand, says, the universe can be silent and indifferent, or it can be silent and conspiratorial."

**Grygum** — *synthesizing*
> "Yes, the universe can be silent and indifferent outside of the fixed framework, and then as we approach it, yes, it gets silent and it gets conspiratorial to compel us toward the invariance."

---

**[Scene tag — The Strong-Weak Hypothesis Crystallizes]**
- Vareth works through the logical structure of Grygum's proposal with him.
- Vareth names and formalizes the "strong-weak hypothesis."

**GM** — *Vareth testing the logic*
> "So what you would say is that Stroud… someone had to… perhaps if I was to theorize this just for a moment, Brother Grygum, you are saying that if someone were to arrive at a particular point, their choices were constrained at that point in time."

**Grygum** — *confirming*
> "Aye."

**GM** — *completing the logic*
> "But who would arrive there was unconstrained."

**Grygum** — *confirming with elaboration*
> "Aye! It could have been Stroud, our great philosopher. It could have been, say, another party of adventurers."

**GM** — *Vareth's response*
> "Hmm."

**Grygum** — *clinching it*
> "But someone would have."

**GM** — *Vareth classifying it*
> "This is a compromise of the Bahamutian school."

**Grygum** — *agreeing*
> "Tis a grand compromise, perhaps."

**GM** — *Vareth formally naming the strong-weak hypothesis and then rushing off*
> "Well, this is very exciting. But, well, this is so exciting. I was planning to share with you a whole bunch of materials, but now I want to go do some research, so he's going to hand you some papers for you to read."

**Grygum** — *accepting with mock resignation*
> "Yes. I accept them. I hope there aren't too many."

**GM** — *Vareth on the vellum question (OOC exchange)*
> "Alright, okay, I'll just cut and paste them."

**Grygum** — *wryly*
> "Vellum is expensive. How much can they afford?"

**Thorin (Joe)** — *OOC, noting the trade*
> "I mean, you gave them a book, they gave you papers back, seems like a fair trade. That's true."

---

**[Scene tag — Vareth Classifies Grygum as a Weak Stroudite]**
- Vareth walks back through the classification before handing over the Stroudite notes.

**GM** — *Vareth's classification*
> "Do you want to share him the, the pamphlet you found? He goes, First, I was going to walk you by the Stroudite school of thought, but we've already established that you are not a Stroudite. Instead, you are a weak Stroudite, rather than a strong Stroudite."

**Grygum** — *admitting ignorance of the jargon*
> "Yes, I did not know all the jargon."

**GM** — *Vareth explaining the distinction*
> "Well, the strong Stroudite says that there are no fixed points, but the weak Stroudite suggests that there is. So you are a weak Stroudite, and a strong Bahamutian around fixed points, and a weak Bahamutian outside of fixed points."

**Grygum** — *pleased*
> "Excellent."

**GM** — *naming the hypothesis formally*
> "So this is… we will call it the strong-weak hypothesis."

**GM** — *Vareth handing over the Stroudite notes*
> "That was not expected. Alright, alright. He goes, well, I'll give you this material, it's what the Stroudites think, I probably… you'll probably think that this is all nonsense."

**Grygum** — *promising to return a marked-up copy*
> "I'll, I'll give you a marked-up version, when I'm, when I'm done."

**GM** — *closing the scene*
> "Alright, okay, alright, so that was, that was, that was cool. Alright, I will."

**Grygum** — *satisfied with his performance*
> "I feel like I handled that competently."

**GM** — *confirming, and noting the new school of thought*
> "Oh, no, you did, you very well did. You've now created a fourth school of thought."
> "He's, like, very excited, because now he's gonna, like, his career's gonna take off."

**Grygum** — *naming it*
> "Yes, the, the Grygum, school of thought."

**GM** — *with relish*
> "Yes, you know, the Grygum school of thought, like, you've just introduced a new philosophical underpinning to, to the North."
